prefix: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in philosophy would.
problem_prompt:
Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in philosophy would. Below is a drawing of all $26$ letters in the English alphabet. As drawn below, some of these letters could be portions of the graph of a function, and some cannot. For example, the $\textsf{O}$ resembles an ellipse, which cannot be part of the graph of a function.

As drawn below, which of these letters could be portions of the graph of a function? (You may not rotate them.)

Give your answer as a list of letters with no spaces or other punctuation between them, in alphabetic order.

$$\begin{array}{c c c c c}
\textsf{A} & \textsf{B} & \textsf{C} & \textsf{D} & \textsf{E}\\\\
\textsf{F} & \textsf{G} & \textsf{H} & \textsf{I} & \textsf{J}\\\\
\textsf{K} & \textsf{L} & \textsf{M} & \textsf{N} & \textsf{O}\\\\
\textsf{P} & \textsf{Q} & \textsf{R} & \textsf{S} & \textsf{T}\\\\
\textsf{U} & \textsf{V} & \textsf{W} & \textsf{X} & \textsf{Y}\\\\
&& \textsf{Z} &&
\end{array}$$
gpt_response:
To determine which letters could be portions of the graph of a function, we need to consider the vertical line test. If a vertical line intersects the graph of a function at more than one point, then the graph fails the vertical line test and is not the graph of a function.

Letters that could be portions of the graph of a function are those that do not intersect themselves when viewed from left to right. Examining the letters provided, we can identify the following as portions of the graph of a function based on their shapes:
- A, B, D, E, F, G, H, I, J, L, N, P, Q, R, S, U, V, Y

Therefore, the letters that could be portions of the graph of a function, when viewed from left to right without intersecting themselves, are: ABDEFGHIJLNPQRSUVY.
